Inflation rises due to food
The accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant increase in food prices.
The November price growth in 13 Eurozone countries was higher than expected, with an annual inflation recording 3.1 per cent after 2.6 per cent in October, the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the Union.
The official forecast predicted only 3 percent, Bloomberg.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian emission banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the basic interest rate with the fact that the decrease, along with rising raw materials prices and decreasing unemployment, would lead to an inflation spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation below 2 percent, but close to them.
According to one of the analysts, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to “remove” inflation so that it has no need to do anything in this matter later.
In Germany, the November inflation of 3.3 per cent is a 15-year record, and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the eurozone has risen up due to the rapidly rising food and energy prices.
The term price of wheat rose by 88 percent, also the price of soya reached its highest value since 1973.
Likewise, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for food oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on the world markets this year rose by 52 percent and last month a barrel of black gold already cost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from this year’s 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, but in 2009 it will already fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the level of 12 months inflation in the next 3-4 months will continue to be approximately 3 percent, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce the interest rates twice during 2008.
