In many places, disinfectants are saved.
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection were registered in hospitals, mainly due to the inappropriate use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions of hospitals, overload of beds, overload of staff stop the disease don’t help, says the primary of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
Recently, a MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatological department of St. John's Hospital.
Antibiotic resistant bacteria was discovered in a man who was hospitalized after a serious traffic accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred in the same place at the beginning of the year.
The patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but shortly afterwards he had to return with MRSA infection and because of the bacteria found in his body, one important operation has not yet been performed.
By December 10th this year, 1,094 hospitalized infections caused by multiresistant pathogens were to the National System of Nesocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, primary member of the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multiresistant pathogens were registered in hospitals with certainty, the others are not known.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin resistant gold staphylococcus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria is carried by a third of people in the nose without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsil inflammation, skin infections, early infections) react well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are administered in excessive or inappropriate extent, bacteria that react well to antibiotics develop bacteria which is highly resistant to antibiotics and which spreads rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of temporary or permanent poor functioning of the immune system in patients with weakened body, low body weight or in patients in years can cause serious hospital infections, such as early infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the senior doctor of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infection belongs to the daily practice in hospitals.
"The infection should not be confused with an epidemic, MRSA is not just there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the pathogen is not examined."
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, the care staff treats them in rubber gloves and in the mask and for their treatment we have the necessary antibiotics," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients hospitalized are first examined if MRSA is present in their body, but the infection cannot always be avoided.
The sample is not in fashion.
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and conditions in home hospitals are not favorable for the prevention of the formation and spread of multiresistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröczová.
Since this infection occurs symptomatically in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should check the hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the MRSA carriers.
However, taking microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not in fashion.
It is also important that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund this examination.
The most cases are so revealed if the patient suffers from a noticeable MRSA infection, the primary member of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, patologies.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, or a microbiological examination should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but the hospitals do not comply with it in all cases.
Microbiological samples are even more rare in the basic or ambulatory treatment of patients, Karolina Böröczová said.
Saving on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is spread among patients most often through medical staff.
Therefore, the washing of hands and the use of gloves and masks plays a very important role, but there are also serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by drop infection and by touch, but in the conditions of home hospitals it is not always possible to isolate infected patients.
The rooms, on the contrary, are often overfilled, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters away.
As Karolina Böröcz noted, unfortunately, we can also encounter that in hospitals that are in a disadvantaged material situation, disinfectants are saved, healers are few and patients a lot, thus the chances of developing infections are increasing.
According to Karolina Böröczová, where necessary protective measures are observed, similar infections are proved less or the further spread of the cause of the disease can be stopped.
Government Programme Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge cost for health insurance companies, therefore it is fighting it everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has written a MRSA prevention program, respectively, reducing its occurrence.
As it seems, the program is successful, according to published data show MRSA infections in England a decreasing trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has ranked the prevention of multiresistent pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these pathogens among its priorities.
