A huge strike.
The League and the National Union of Workers' Councils (MOSZ) will set up a strike committee on Friday to coordinate Monday's unlimited strike.
The public assembly will be held on Saturday, and on Monday - on the day of the final vote on the health insurance law - the work will be stopped.
The event will surely cause serious traffic interruptions, as the railway transport will almost completely stop and employees of the Budapest Transport Enterprise (BKV) will strike within 13 hours.
On Friday afternoon, the League associations will meet the National Union of Workers' Councils with the details of the jointly organized Monday strike.
The strike commission LIGA-MOSZ will also be formed, which will coordinate the action on Monday.
On Saturday, a public assembly will be held, and from Monday, the trade unions joining the strike will stop their work for an indefinite time unless there is an agreement with the government.
This means that the deadline for the end of the strike, which will begin on the day of the parliamentary vote on the health insurance law, has not been set.
If the Parliament eventually fails to adopt the Health Insurance Act, the trade unions will immediately withdraw the call to strike.
However, if the legislation is voted, the strike committees will meet and decide on the further procedure.
According to the Monday agenda of the Parliament meeting, it is also possible that the law on health insurance will be voted only in late evening or night hours.
Because of the strike that starts on Monday, it is possible to count with serious traffic interruptions: on the railway work will be stopped for an unlimited time, in the morning part of the Budapest public transport and more than half of Volán companies can stop.
At the same time, many places in the country will also be closed half of the route.
A number of trade unions and civil organizations have joined the strike call, whose list is constantly updated on the League’s website.
Some organizations announced an unlimited strike, while others announced a temporary stop of work.
Until Thursday afternoon, the Hungarian State Railways (MÁV) and the Independent Railway Workers' Union (VDSZSZ) were unable to agree even on sufficient services, while the start of Christmas holidays increasing number of people travel by railway.
According to the previous communications, from the start of the operation until 13 hours will be strike at the BKV, from 7 to 9 hours in the morning at the Budapest Airport, a four-hour strike is organized by the LIGA Energy Industry Workers' Union, to the 2-, respectively 2-8-hour stop of work called for by the Pedagogs' Union and the Democratic Pedagogs' Union.
The Union of Hungarian Doctors will strike alternately throughout the country, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers (EDDSZ), which belongs to the Cooperative Forum of Trade Unions (SZEF), will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four requirements formulated by the League is that the government should revoke the proposal for the health insurance reform and submit a new concept for public discussion.
The second requirement is that a new pension calculation method, which is valid from the next year, be introduced gradually.
Thirdly, to ensure that early retirement for the relevant sectors of employment can be included in the system before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is that the Independent Railway Workers’ Union (VDSZSZ), which belongs to the League’s trade union, does not accept the Ministry of Economy and Transport’s offer on railway shifts and is expecting a different offer.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases Country Risk
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért movement in August of this year, according to the Risk Analysis Division of the Political Capital Institute, increased the political risk of Hungary and the entire region in several ways.
The company’s “risk warning” states that, in the context of the Hungarian Guard’s activities, the greatest political risk is that, “by focusing on the existing ethnic tension between the Romans and the Romans in Hungary, violent ethnic conflicts can occur within a short time.”
The main reason is that the Hungarian Guard’s political strategy is likely aimed at provoking such action – the research institut adds.
As he writes, all of this can be explained by one of the greatest negligence of Hungarian political leaders: “the public discussion on the Roman issue was left by the leaders of public life to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy on the Rom-Hungarian contradiction.”
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists, and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, according to the Research Institute, under the influence of the great attention of domestic and foreign media “have greatly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially with regard to the belief in the stability of the country and its democratic maturity.”
The Institute reminds: part of the reorganization of Hungarian radical and ultra-right groups, which since autumn 2006 is getting more and more publicity and wealth, is that in Hungary since summer 2007 have been formed several organizations, which themselves call the associations of "National Homeland Defense".
“The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as a civil association, while openly declaring – even armed – the willingness of their members to perform defence tasks (in the case of natural disasters, attack on the homeland, disturbance of order), in addition with the indication of the incapacity of the police, the army, or the state,” he added.
He further notes that all of this is done in a way that seeks to pack the various political efforts built on the resistance of society to politics and the parties to civil clothes.
The emphasis on civility and the form of the association, therefore, in the case of these groups, does not only serve to avoid the legal failures of judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is an increasing risk factor also in terms of neighbouring relations.
“In recent months they have pointed to the Hungarian Guard right in several neighbouring states as a potential source of danger, and the ultra-nationalist political leaders of some neighbouring countries, referring to the formation of the Hungarian Guard, want to apologize for their own anti-Hungarian policy.
All of this can affect the political stability of the region,” he added.
According to the Research Institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not a unique phenomenon, so the political risks for the region as a whole have increased.
The activity of the Hungarian Guard is similar to the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced by the ultra-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
On the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard stands the massive Roman rebellion that exploded in one of the Sofia districts (Krasna Poljana).
This BNU used to establish the Guard with the fact that the organization's goal is "National Homeland Defense".
