The Ministers of the Czech Republic and representatives of the European Commission signed a total of nine operational programmes, of which the Czech Republic can obtain in the coming years 14 billion euros (approximately 365 billion SEK).
This is about half of the total amount that the Czech Republic can obtain from Brussels between 2007 and 2013.
Approximately 125 billion SEK will be spent from seven operational programs to the regions.
Czech companies will be able to earn about 100 billion SEK from the Entrepreneurship and Innovation Program.
The most money, up to 150 billion, will be directed to transportation.
The Transport Program is the largest operational program and accounts for up to 22 percent of the funds that the Czech Republic can receive from the funds.
These funds will increase the budget of the State Transport Infrastructure Fund, which will be managed next year in the amount of SEK 90,8 billion.
The Entrepreneurship and Innovation Programme aims to serve entrepreneurs and companies to gain funds for innovative business.
Companies should gain funding for the introduction of new technologies, for industrial research, but also for the introduction of more efficient organizational methods.
So far, the Czech Republic has been among the least successful countries in the EU funds.
