After more than 60 years in a secret regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are open to the public.
47 million archive documents stored in a length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were until that time accessible only for “humanitarian” purposes, i.e. individually and namely, at the request of the former victim or its authorized persons.
The 11 archive governments – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this Agreement by all States is over, the opening of yesterday has come into effect.
Sensitive Information
The free access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow to investigate “especially the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the health of forced workers,” explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Croix-rouge (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to make these nominal documents available to the public, due to the sensitive nature of some information.
What are the presumed homosexuality or mental disabilities of some victims of deportation.
The registers of concentration camps or arrests compiled by the Gestap were collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced work subjected to civil citizens, bringing them evidence of their internation in order to open the way to their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is only a limited benefit.
"These documents cannot expect anything fundamentally new," said in 2006 Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for the Study of Antisemitism at the Technische Universität of Berlin.
