Congress approves MiFID transposition from 1 November
In conjunction with the parliamentary talks, which were concluded today by Congress voting on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the draft law, the government submitted a public hearing of a regulation that develops the new law, in order for both to enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of each party agreed to highlight the efforts of the MPs and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard to ensure the protection of investors and the detailed regulation of the activities of the entities necessary for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernization of the financial markets while strengthening the investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the individual supervisory bodies of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable the provision of financial consultancy services to both specialized companies and natural or legal persons, and will create a new type of financial services companies (ESIS), financial consultancy companies (AFI) that connect to securities companies, securities intermediaries and portfolio-managing companies.
Furthermore, the number of operations with financial instruments will be expanded by joining multilateral trading and order internalization systems to regulated secondary markets, which will compete with current stock exchange brokers.
The law also obliges investment services companies to spread on the market information on the key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and methods of risk management, and requires a report of all the operations carried out to simplify the supervision by CNMV.
During the discussions in Congress’s Trade Commission, a number of adjustments were included, among which it stands out that securized claims were considered a “complex” financial instrument due to the high risk for the investor, which was demonstrated by what happened in the U.S. with high-risk mortgage debt (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally designate the functions that may be held by the Bachelor in Economics and Business Management for 30 years after the Royal Decree was approved in 1977, which designates the professional functions dedicated to economists.
At the same time, the Senate included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary who will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide products trading and customer acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
